126: ## Do's and Don'ts
127: 
128: ### Do
129: - Use 95px Whyte weight 400 as the only display size — never split into bold/regular variants, let the SIZE carry hierarchy.
130: - Hold the page to four colors total: #ffffff canvas, #212529 ink, #000000 for the heaviest moments, #e4e4e4 hairlines.
131: - Use 0px border-radius on every component — cards, buttons, images, tags. Sharp corners are the brand.
132: - Set section padding to 100px top and bottom, with 50px horizontal gutters — the breathing room IS the layout.
133: - Let product photography supply color: when a colored element is needed, use a real product image rather than introducing a new brand color.
134: - Use 1px outlined buttons with 6px horizontal / 1px vertical padding — the bar should feel like a typographic underline, not a conventional CTA.
135: - Keep the body line-height at 1.50 and the display line-height at 1.00 — never let the giant headlines feel airy.
136: 
137: ### Don't
138: - Don't introduce a chromatic accent color for buttons, links, badges, or icons — there is no brand color in this system, the packaging supplies the only saturation.
139: - Don't use drop shadows, gradients, or blur effects — surfaces are flat, defined only by hairline borders.
140: - Don't use rounded corners anywhere, even on tags or avatars — everything is a sharp rectangle.
141: - Don't use bold (weight 600+) or light (weight 300) cuts of Whyte — weight 400 is the only voice, all hierarchy is typographic scale.
142: - Don't add icons, emojis, or decorative glyphs to the UI — the eye mark and the wordmark are the only marks.
143: - Don't split the giant wordmark into multiple lines or hyphenate it — "CAFE", "HOURS", "INTRA" each occupy one line at 95px.
144: - Don't apply a hover color change to links — the underline is the affordance, not a color shift.
